Abstract

Well-managed fisheries are critical for supporting healthy ocean ecosystems, coastal livelihoods, and food security for millions of people. Many communities lack the resources to implement effective fisheries management. No-take marine reserves are a relatively simple tool to conserve biodiversity and provide fishery benefits. Although empirical examples of fishery benefits from reserves are becoming more prevalent, the short-term economic impacts of establishing marine reserves are rarely considered (note that for this paper, the we refer solely to fishing when we consider economic impacts). In this paper we simulate fisheries for six species commonly caught in coastal fisheries in order to demonstrate the time required for a no-take reserve to provide a net improvement in the economic well-being of a fishing community. Our results show that while conservation benefits accrue rapidly, more than a decade is often required to provide net fisheries benefits, even under circumstances favorable for reserves. We explore a suite of strategies for mitigating these short-term economic losses, including flexible reserve designs, rights-based management, and loans. Our results indicate that combinations of these strategies can greatly reduce the short-term economic impacts of no-take marine reserves. Our findings provide mechanisms for improving the viability of no-take marine reserves as tools for fisheries management and conservation.

Introduction

More than 260 million people across the globe earn their livelihood in fishing related industries (Teh et al. 2014). Fish is a primary source of protein to over one billion people (FAO 2011). Yet the sustainability of the fishing industry and the potential for wild capture fisheries to indefinitely feed a growing population is dependent on the implementation and enforcement of effective systems of governance and management. No-take marine reserves (hereafter reserves), areas set off-limits to fishing, are a widely used tool for protecting fish populations and are known to provide key conservation benefits that can improve ecosystem services to coastal environments. Conservation benefits of marine reserves include the maintenance of spatial population structure of fish stocks (Berkeley et al. 2004; White et al. 2008; Rassweiler et al. 2012), protection of essential fish habitat, increased species diversity and fish biomass (Lester et al. 2009), and can serve as reference areas to set local management regulations and disentangle the effects of fishing from environmental variability (Wilson et al. 2013). Enhanced biological production inside reserves can benefit adjacent fisheries through adult spillover (Roberts and Polunin 1991; Allison et al. 1998; McClanahan and Mangi 2008) and larval export (Cudney-Bueno et al. 2009; Pelc et al. 2010), especially in situations where the size of the reserve is larger than the adult home range size, and smaller than the scale of larval dispersal (Gerber et al. 2003). Reserves can also serve as a hedge against changes in environmental conditions (Stefansson and Rosenberg 2005; Costello and Polasky 2008)) and as an effective means of protecting spatially complex marine populations (White et al. 2008; Rassweiler et al. 2012).

Marine reserves are increasingly proposed as a mechanism for simultaneously contributing to strong conservation outcomes and improving the productivity of fisheries (Gaines et al. 2010). This argument is often made in the context of developing world fisheries, which may have little capacity to perform more complex fishery management practices (such as quotas, size limits, or effort restrictions)(Holland and Brazee 1996). In fact, reserves have a long history as fishery management tools in many island nations (Johannes 1978, 2002). However, the ability marine reserves to provide fishery benefits is dependent on a suite of factors, including the size of reserve relative to the home range size of the species, the dispersal potential, geographic extent of the stock, as well as the status of the fishery prior to implementation of reserves (Sanchirico and Wilen 2001; Smith and Wilen 2003; Sanchirico et al. 2006; Costello and Polasky 2008; White et al. 2008; Rassweiler et al. 2012). Moreover, the implementation of marine reserves necessarily reduces the spatial extent of the fishery, often limiting take in prime fishing grounds and concentrating effort into smaller regions of the coast (Halpern et al. 2004).

The potential and challenges of utilizing reserves as fishery management tools have been well studies then (Hilborn et al. 2004), though it is worth noting that the vast majority of this work is simulation based, and little empirical evidence of the fishery impacts of reserves is available (see Fletcher et al. 2014 for an empirical paper that found no evidence of enhanced fishery production from the Great Barrier Reef marine reserve). There is a critical gap in the the literature concerning fisheries and reserves though; the economic impacts over time. Nearly all of the published research on the topic has considered the long-term (or equilibrium) economic impacts of implementing a marine reserve. However, while the long-term impacts are critical to understanding the interactions between reserves and fisheries, from the perspective of fishing community’s the short-term impacts may be of much greater consequence. Depending on the time horizon that a community is able or willing to consider, a reserve that provides long-term fishery benefits may provide no practical benefit to today’s fishers and decision makers. Alternatively, even in conditions in which a community will perceive benefits in the future, they may have to endure years of reduced fishing income and food until those benefits arrive.These short-term consequences of reserves can have profound implications on the financial health and food security of fishing communities, affecting local support and buy in for enforcement policies, trust in management and supporting organizations, and ultimately the sustainability of the fishery itself.

Brown et al. [@-Brown2014] provides an important contribution to our understanding of the short-term impacts of marine reserves. They illustrate that their are often important tradeoffs between short-term and long-term economic fishing benefits from reserves, and that alternative strategies for designing those reserves (how large they are and how that size changes over time) can dramatically affect the short-term economic effects of a reserve.

[@-Brown2014] launches an important discussion on the ways in we might choose to design reserves in order to provide fishery benefits, and the ways in which the consequences of those choices can be communicated to fishing communities. In particular, they point out that reserves designed around long-term benefits have substantial short-term costs. Our paper builds of array of design and finance based solutions to mitigating short-term economic impacts created by marine reserves. We ask: 1. How does the size of a reserve affect the magnitude and timing of net fishery benefits? 2. How capable are design and financial solutions of offsetting short-term economic losses? 3. What reserve strategy maximizes a community’s net benefit?

We find that for many reef-fish species, reserves may struggle to provide net fishing benefits at a time scale that is of value to fishing communities, but that design and financial mechanisms show strong potential for offsetting these losses.

Methods

Operating Model

We analyzed 6 different species, intended to capture a range of life-history traits of species often targeted by tropical developing country fisheries. Our model is single species, age-structured and assumed to be closed with respect to larval and adult emigration and immigration. The spatial configuration of the fishery includes 100 unique patches with wrapped edges connected by larval and adult movement. The model tracks stock numbers, biomass, fishery yields over time.

Life history values were drawn from stock assessments where possible, in order to help ensure reliable and consistent values(Table.1). The recruitment model (or the functional for of the density dependence relationship) was selected from the possible structures outlined in Babcock & MacCall (2011) using expert judgement. The Range parameter scales the number of patches moved by adults in a time step, with 100% indicating total mixing and 0% a completely sedentary species.

Life history values used. m is natural mortality, Linf, k, and t0 are the Von Bertalanffy growth parameters, Age/Length Ma50 are the respective age or length at which the 50% of the individuals have reached sexual maturity, h is steepness, and the roman numeral under “Density Dependence” corresponds with the density dependence form from Babcock & MacCall 2011 that was used. Values with * were assumed

The number of fish in patch i at age a at the beginning of year t+1 is

  1. \(N_{i,a,t+1} = R_{i,t+1}\) if a = 0

  2. \(N_{i,a,t+1} = N_{i,a-1,t}e^{-M-F_{i,t}\upsilon_{a-1}}\) if \(1 \leq a < x\)

  3. \(N_{i,a,t+1} = N_{i,x-1,t}e^{-M-F_{i,t}\upsilon_{x-1}} + N_{i,x,t}e^{-M-F_{i,t}\upsilon_{x}}\) if \(a = x\)

where Ri,tis the recruitment in patch i in year t, Fi,t is the instantaneous fishing mortality in patch i in year t, \(\upsilon_{a}\) is the selectivity of the fishing gear for a fish at age a (which we assume to be 1 for all ages), M is the instantaneous natural mortality, and x is the maximum age recorded in the model (the plus group). This model assumes that the biological parameters of each species are homogeneous across space and time.

The simulations begin at an unfished equilibrium using a specified unfished initial recruitment in each patch i, Ri,0 such that

  1. \(N_{i,a} = R_{i,0}\) if a = 0

  2. \(N_{i,a} = N_{i,a-1}e^{-M}\) if \(1 \leq a < x\)

  3. \(N_{i,a} = \frac{N_{i,x-1}e^{-M}}{1-e^{-M}}\) if \(a = x\)

The population is then fished down at a specified open access harvest rate in both patches to equilibrium conditions. We set this rate such that biomass over biomass at maximum sustainable yield (B/BMSY) is equal to 0.25 at equilibrium, representing an overfished fishery. We chose this level as the benefits of reserve formation were positively (and relatively linearly) related to the degree of overfishing. Starting at an overfished state then provides an optimistic estimation of the potential benefits of reserve formation.

The average length (la) of fish in each age class is calculated using a von Bertalanffy growth equation

  1. \(l_{a} = L_{inf}(1-e^{-k(t-t_{0})})\)

and then converted to average weight (wa) using:

  1. \(w_{a}=b_{1}l_{a}^{b_{2}}\)

We assume habitat quality to be the same in all patches. Adult movement at each time step among the 100 patches is then calculated using a Gaussian dispersal kernel

  1. \(p_{i,j}=e^{\frac{-d_{i,j}^{2} }{2\sigma_{A}^{2}}}\)

where pi,j is the proportion of fish moving from area i to area j, and di,j is the distance between area i and area j. The model parameter \(\sigma_{A}\) defines the movement range for the species, and is scaled by the Range parameter. We wrap movement in order to remove edge effects. The relative proportions are then normalized so that the total proportion of fish moving from area i to any area sum to one. The number of fish in each age group one and older after movement are then

  1. \(N_{i,a,t} = \sum^{100}_{j=1} N_{j,a,t}p_{i,j}\)

To calculate recruitment each year in each patch we use the recruitment models described in Babcock & MacCall (2011), in order to allow the nature of density dependence to vary among species (for example, pre or post settlement density dependence).

Fishery Dynamics

The catch in each patch at each time step is calculated as

  1. \(Y_{i,t} = \sum_{a}(N_{i,a,t}e^{-F_{i,t}\upsilon_{a}})\)

We assume a closed population of fishers, where the number of fishers does not change with the implementation of a reserve (no emigration or immigration of boats), such that the effort from the reserve area is displaced to the fished area. This is intended to reflect a subsistence style fishery, with few alternative livelihoods besides fishing. Fishing effort is scaled by the relative commercial biomass,\(\bar{B}_{i}\), in each patch where

  1. \(\bar{B}_{i}= \frac{B_{i}}{\sum_{i}B_{i}}\)

  2. \(F_{i,t}=F_{pNTZ}(1+P_{NTZ})\bar{B}_{i}\)

Where FpNTZ is the total possible instantaneous fishing pressure in the patch before the implementation of the reserve, and PNTZ is the fraction of patches that are in a reserve.

Reserve Implementation

We simulate a series of reserve implementation scenarios using the above operating model and fleet dynamics. A given scenario is defined by an terminal reserve size (% of area in a reserve), an “intercept” (% of the area in a reserve in year 1), and a “slope” (% of run years at which the reserve reaches terminal size). In effect then we allow the final size, initial size, and rate at which the reserve reaches its final size to vary. We apply a fine-scale grid of factorial combinations of reserve size, intercept, and slope to each of the 6 species included in this paper, providing an outline of the potential outcomes of reserve implementation.

Metrics

Throughout each scenario we keep track of live biomass of fish in the water and fishery yields over time. Net present balance (NPB) is our primary metric of performance, where NPB represents the present value of the cumulative yield benefits of a given reserve strategy relative to the status quo, calculated as

  1. \(NPB_{s} = \sum^{T}_{t=0} \frac{Y_{s,t}-Y_{q}}{(1+r)^{t}}\)

for any given species, where t is time, Y represents fishing yields, s is reserve implementation strategy, q is the status quo, r is the economic discount rate, and T is a specified number of years after reserve implementation in which NPB is calculated and compared across scenarios and species. We calculate the year at which NPB surpasses zero (increased benefits have compensated for short-term losses). NPB is an important output, since it reflects the net benefit that a community perceives from a given reserve strategy, relative to their benefit without the reserve. Alternatively, present balance (PB), the discounted difference between yields of a given reserve strategy and the status quo in year t, while important and a commonly presented metric, may not be as meaningful to a community (e.g. a 1 ton improvement over the status quo in year 10 of a reserve strategy may be of little value if 1,000 tons have been lost in years 1 through 9; see Fig.1 for an illustration of these concepts). Dawn walk us through cartoon illustration here

Illustration of the trajectory of net benefits following a reserve

We chose a discount rate of 0.XX for our NPB calculations. This is based on Johnson & Saunders (2014) and Curtis (2002), which found discount rates of fishermen of ~0.22 (mean) and ~ 0.35 (median), respectively.

Financial Mechanisms

We also analyze two potential financial mechanisms for offsetting short-term fishery losses stemming from the reserve; a loan system and a value added system. The total relative loss in yields experienced by the fishery for a given scenario s is

  1. \(O_{s} = -\sum^{T}_{t=0} min(0,Y_{s,t}-Y_{q})\)

Where O~s is the amount of yield lost relative to the status quo over time period T. Under the loan strategy, a non-governmental organization, government, or private investor could provide a community with a loan to offset the initial losses from implementing a reserve, with a goal of being repaid by the future fishery benefits resulting from enhanced fishery productivity. The fishing community requests a loan totaling Os. The surplus available to pay the loan back over time T are equal to

  1. \(S_{s} = -\sum^{T}_{t=0} max(0,Y_{s,t}-Y_{q})\)

Where Ss is the total positive difference in yields (if any) for a given reserve scenario s,over what the fishery would have experienced under the status quo.

For a given loan interest rate i for a loan of duration T, the total loan payments are equal to

  1. \(C = Tp( \frac{\frac{i}{p}{O}}{1-(1+i)^{-Tp}})\)

where p is the number of payments per year. Setting the time window of the loan to T of 10 years with p of 4 payments per year, we then use the optim package in R (R Core Team 2015) to estimate the highest interest rate i (%) that the community could afford in order to pay back a 10-year loan such that Cs,i <= Ss; meaning that the total loan payments must be less than or equal to the surplus generated by the reserve. The higher the maximum potential interest rate, the more viable the loan is.

For the value increase scenario, we implicitly assume a status quo value of $1 per unit weight (though this is an arbitrary choice that does not in fact matter). We then ask by what percent the value of the catch caught under a given scenario s would have to increase in order to completely offset the greatest loss of yields seen across all years

  1. \(P_{s} = 100(\frac{Y_{q}}{Y_{q}+min(Y_{s}-Y_{q})}-1))\)

Reserves often face competing objectives between long-term conservation benefits and short-term economic benefits. This can be empirically illustrated by considering the cumulative biomass of fish in the water over time with a discount rate r of 0 (long-term conservation planner, \(B_{r_{0}}\)) vs. the net present benefits of the reserve over time with a discount rate r > 0 (in this case we consider 0.1, \(Y_{r_{0.1}}\))). In order to consider the relative utility of a given reserve strategy s we assign a weighting parameter \(\alpha\) that can take any value from 0 to 1, such that total utility U is calculated as

  1. \(U_{s} = \alpha(\frac{Y_{r_{0.1},s}}{\sum_{s}Y_{r_{0.1},s}}) + (1-\alpha)(\frac{B_{r_{0},s}}{\sum_{s}B_{r_{0},s}})\)

This allows us to calculate utility focused solely on discounted fishery benefits (\(\alpha\)=1), long-term conservation benefits (\(\alpha\)=0), or any relative weighting in between).

Results

Discount Rate

We first provide an illustration of the importance of the assigned discount rate r, using yellowtail snapper. The discount rate reflects the degree to which money today is favored over money tomorrow; the higher the rate, the less a community (or individual) values something in the future relative to today. For a given discount rate, we find the reserve scenario s (combination of terminal size, starting size, and slope) that maximizes the community’s utility per Eq.19 . So with a discount rate of 0 (which means that a dollar in the future has the same value as a dollar today) the NPB is simply the cumulative sum of the yield balances over time. Under this scenario, the optimal policy for yellowtail snapper is to put a subtantial portion of the fishery into a reserve for nearly a decade, reducing the reserve size once the fishery begins to recover, resulting in substantial economic gains for the fishery by year 50.

A discount rate of 0.05 is the default value in much of the economic literature (CITATION XXX). Under this reality, the optimal scenarios from the perspective of a community designing a reserve today would be to implement a reserve covering 25%-50% of the fishery, and then reduce it’s size more quickly than under the r=0 scenario. This strategy results in a net benefit for the community in slightly over 10 years, meaning that from the community’s perspective, they would need to feel confident that they will be there and fishing for at least 10 years in order for a (even optimally designed) reserve to be worthwhile for them. Increasing the discount rate to even 0.2 (which may still be low for many artisanal fisheries) results in an optimal reserve that starts at 10% and quickly shrinks, resulting in almost no net benefit to the community.

Example NPB trajectories under optimal reserve scenario under different discount rates for yellowtail snapper

Sensitivity to Design

Results up to here show that yes reserves can take time to provide benefits if at all, design can help a bit, multi-species adds another layer though many species do just about as well with similar species reserves as they do with their optimal one.

  • Without discounting, things are looking good, in the long view almost any reserve will help, some by a lot.
  • But, even with moderate discounting this dissapears
  • So from a management task, this is a problem. We might want a reserve to get those long term fishery benefits, or for conservation goals. But, with even a moderate discount rate, reflective of the ones seen in the lit, it’s unlikely you’ll get community support if you’re honest about the timing to benefits
  • So, what’s the solution?

We first consider how sensitive our results are to implementing the incorrect terminal reserve size. Or in other words, we consider our results under a range of terminal reserve sizes, and ask how sensitive our results are to being in a particular window. If it’s small, unlikely that we’ll find it in the real world.

  • For bumphead, grouper, and snapper peak NPB occurs at around 10% reserve size, neagative by about 20%. Emperor much larger. Blacknose shark and trevally not possible. This suggests that reserves less than 20% viable from an NPB perspective for many common species, not so much beyond that. But, it’s not knife edged (optimal or bust)

NPB with discount rate of 0.2 under possible terminal reserve sizes for each species

So, under static scenario we see that NPB is somewhat sensitive to terminal reserve size, but not extremely; for a general class of reserves under 20% seems possible, though the scale of it matters. What about other metrics?

  • We see that even though positive NPB is possible up to the sizes seen in Fig.4, it takes a long time to achieve. So, while the ability to break even at all is somewhat insensitive to reserve size, the amount of time required increases almost exponentially in reserve size.

Our results show though that while design has some potential for offsetting the short-term economic impacts of reserves, there are substantial challenges for relying solely on design as a solution. First, we see that reserves greater than 25% have very little chance of providing positive NPB for the majority of common reef fish studied here (Fig.5). However, numerous studies suggest that from a conservation perspective marine reserves covering 25-30% of range are a minimum recommended amount (XX CITATION). Our results show then that reserves designed in this fashion may struggle to provide perceived net benefits to many communities. In addition, even in the cases where NPB is highly positive, the time to achieve that NPB is quite long should the timing be NB not NPBXX (Fig.6). Therefore, even when benefits accrue there is still a period of losses that must be dealt with. For both of these reasons, we can consider the potential of our financial instruments.

10 year loans don’t work well except for philanthropy

Maximum % interest rate payable by a fishery for each species across a range of terminal reserve sizes

The percent price increase required increased almost exponentially with the reserve size. However, the price increase shows the potential to offset much larger reserves, with increases of 20% capable of offsetting reserves closer to 30% in many cases. In addition, relatively small price increases (<20%) are sufficient to bring species such as blacknose shark and silver trevally, which were not benefited by design or loans, into a positive situation

  • Price increases are good but not feasible for things like 50% reserves

% Price increase required by a fishery for each species across a range of terminal reserve sizes

Optimal Impacts

We found the scenario s that maximized utility U (with an \(\alpha\) of 0.5, signifying equal weighting between long and short-term benefits) for each species (Fig.1).

  • Even under optimal some species can’t get positive NPB with this discount rate
  • NPB takes longer than yield surplus
  • Note that unlike Brown, shrinking is best if you have discounting and benefits are possible (growing is only best if you can’t achieve benefits in the discounted window)
  • The point of these is basically to say that we can replicateish results from Brown, and now we’re going to build on them

NPB trajectories under optimal reserve scenario. Size of circle represents % of ares in reserve, color the yield surplus in a given year

MPAs are commonly used as a tool for multi-species management, especially in the context simulated by this paper. As such, we should consider not only the effects of the the reserve on individual species but on the group of species. To address this we took the optimal reserve strategy for each species, and then applied it to each other species, to ask how far from the optimal NPB the other species’ reserve strategy forced the target species NPB (Fig 2-3)

  • The basic point here is if you use a reserve designed for one species on another, how badly do you do? Need to do some tweaking here to get the color scales to come out right.

Discussion

  • Lower the discount rate!

  • Design isn’t all that important, within certain bounds, conditional on any benefits being possible

  • NPB matters: Even if there’s a huge net benefit in the future, it doesn’t matter if it takes 1000 years to get there
  • As Brown et al. (2014) showed, timing can be a problem with reserves
  • The good news
    • For clades of species (snapper, emperor, grouper, parrot), you can get away with not having the exact right reserve, both individually and across species
    • reasonable price increases could offset the valley of death
    • Complications life slope and intercept help, but aren’t deal breakers
  • The bad news
    • Even a small discount rate quickly reduces the potential to achieve positive NPB: while there might be benefits to the long term planner good luck with the community. (Teh et al. 2014) as evidence of high discount rate in artisanal fisheries.
    • Some species aren’t possible
    • 10 year Loans don’t seem viable
    • Especially with a discount rate, the optimal or viable reserve size is quite a bit smaller than the target side touted by conservationists.
  • The take home
    • Design can certainly help, but it’s somewhat finicky, and even done perfectly, might not then achieve the conservation objectives if the community has a strong discount rate
    • That leaves financial mechanisms. Which we show have some promise
    • We’ll probably need RBFM to make them happen though
